The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reporting amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expense during the reporting period. Estimates and assumptions are used in accounting for, among other things, the valuation of acquisition-related assets and liabilities, allowances for uncollectable accounts, taxes and related valuation allowances, loss contingencies, fair value measurements, impairment assessments, useful lives of long-lived assets and share-based compensation. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 15000000 475323000 146801000 443891000 153267000 4700000 1600000 4500000 1400000 1400000 500000 1400000 400000 3075000 3531000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">9. REVOLVING CREDIT FACILITY &amp; BANK BORROWINGS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Senior </font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On September 25, 2009, Crocs entered into a Revolving Credit and Security Agreement (</font><font style="display: inline;">as amended, </font><font style="display: inline;">the &#x201C;Credit Agreement&#x201D;) with the lenders named therein and PNC Bank, National Association ("PNC"), as a lender and administrative agent for the lenders. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On April 2, 2015, Crocs entered into the Sixth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;Sixth Amendment&#x201D;) pursuant to which certain terms of the Credit Agreement were amended. The Sixth Amendment primarily amended certain definitions of the financial covenants to be more favorable to Crocs including (i) setting the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through December 31, 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.15</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through March 31, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.25</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for each quarte</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">r thereafter, (ii)&nbsp;setting the leverage r</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">atio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">4.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 through March 31, 2016 and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">3.75</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for each quarter thereafter and&nbsp;(iii) reducing the Company&#x2019;s global cash requirement from </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$100</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On September 1, 2015, the Company entered into the Eighth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement (the &#x201C;Eighth Amendment&#x201D;) pursuant to which certain terms of the Credit Agreement were amended. The Eighth Amendment primarily amended certain definitions of the financial covenants to become more favorable to the Company including (i) increasing the exclusion of ca</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">sh and non-cash char</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ges from the EBITDAR calculation to up to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$85.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, not to exceed </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$65.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million with respect to cash charges, (ii) setting the minimum fixed charge coverage ratio to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">0.95</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00 for the period ended September 30, 2015, (iii) allowing up to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$40.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million in stock repurchases to be made during the quarter ended September 30, 2015, (iv) suspending stock repurchases if the fixed charge coverage ratio is less than </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.00</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> to 1.00, and (v) eliminating the administrative agent basket through December 31, 2015.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The Credit Agreement enables Crocs to borrow up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$100.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, with the ability to increase commitments to </font><font style="display: inline;">$125.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million subject to certain conditions, and is currently set to mature in </font><font style="display: inline;">December 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. The Credit Agreement is available for working capital, capital expenditures, permitted acquisitions, reimbursement of drawings under letters of credit, and permitted dividends, distributions, purchases, redemptions and retirements of equity interests. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement are secured by all of the Company&#x2019;s assets including all receivables, equipment, general intangibles, inventory, investment property, subsidiary stock and intellectual property. Borrowings under the Credit Agreement bear interest at a variable rate. For domestic rate loans, the interest rate is equal to the highest of (i) the daily federal funds open rate as quoted by ICAP North America, Inc. plus </font><font style="display: inline;">0.5%</font><font style="display: inline;">, (ii) PNC's prime rate and (iii) a daily LIBOR rate plus </font><font style="display: inline;">1.0%</font><font style="display: inline;">, in each case there is an additional margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">0.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">1.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. For LIBOR rate loans, the interest rate is equal to a LIBOR rate plus a margin ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;">1.25%</font><font style="display: inline;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;">2.00%</font><font style="display: inline;"> based on certain conditions. The Credit Agreement requires monthly interest payments with respect to domestic rate loans and at the end of each interest period with respect to LIBOR rate loans. The Credit Agreement further provides for a limit on the issuance of letters of credit to a maximum of </font><font style="display: inline;">$20.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. The Credit Agreement contains provisions requiring Crocs to maintain compliance with certain restrictive and financial covenants. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, the Company had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the Credit Agreement. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, the Company had outstanding letters of credit of $</font><font style="display: inline;">1.5</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which were reserved against the borrowing base under the terms of the Credit Agreement. As of September 30, 2015, the Company was not in compliance with the fixed charge coverage ratio and </font><font style="display: inline;">the </font><font style="display: inline;">leverage ratio under the Credit Agreement. On November 3, 2015, the Company entered into the Ninth Amendment to Amended and Restated Credit Agreement pursuant to which the Company received a waiver from the lenders of the financial covenant violations as of September 30, 2015 and the Credit Agreement was amended to </font><font style="display: inline;">allow for up to </font><font style="display: inline;">$15</font><font style="display: inline;">.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million in stock repurchases</font><font style="display: inline;"> in the fourth quarter of 2015.</font><font style="display: inline;"> The Company anticipates it will be in compliance with its covenants as of December 31, 2015, however, there can be no assurance that the Company will be in compliance at that date. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Asia Pacific Revolving Credit Facility</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On August 28, 2015, a Crocs subsidiary entered into a revolving credit facility agreement with HSBC Bank (China) Company Limited, Shanghai Branch (&#x201C;HSBC&#x201D;) as the lender. The revolving credit facility enables Crocs to borrow uncommitted dual currency revolving loan facilities up to RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">40.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, or the USD equivalent, and import facilities up to RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">60.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, or the USD equivalent, however, the total combined facility amount may not exceed an aggregate facility limit of RMB </font><font style="display: inline;">60.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million. This revolving credit facility</font><font style="display: inline;"> supports possible future net working capital needs in China. For loans denominated in USD, the interest rate is </font><font style="display: inline;">2.1%</font><font style="display: inline;"> per annum plus LIBOR for three months or any other period as may be determined by HSBC at the end of each interest period. For loans denominated in RMB, interest equals the one year benchmark lending rate effective on the loan drawdown date set forth by the People&#x2019;s Bank of China with a </font><font style="display: inline;">10%</font><font style="display: inline;"> mark-up and is payable on the maturity date of the related loan. </font><font style="display: inline;">The revolving credit facility is guaranteed by Crocs, Inc. </font><font style="display: inline;">and certain accounts receivables in China are pledged as security under the revolving credit facility. </font><font style="display: inline;">The revolving credit facility contains provisions requiring Crocs to maintain compliance with certain restrictive covenants and as of September 30, 2015, Crocs was in compliance with all relevant covenants. As of September 30, 2015, Crocs had </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> outstanding borrowings under the revolving credit facility.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Long-Term Bank Borrowings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">On December 10, 2012, Crocs entered into a Master Installment Payment Agreement (&#x201C;Master IPA&#x201D;) with PNC in which PNC financed the Company&#x2019;s recent implementation of a new enterprise resource planning (&#x201C;ERP&#x201D;) system, which began in October 2012 and was substantially completed in early 2015. The terms of each note payable, under the Master IPA, consist of a fixed interest rate and payment terms based on the amount borrowed and the timing of activity throughout the </font><font style="display: inline;">implementation of the ERP system. The Master IPA is subject to cross-default, cross-termination, and is co-terminous with the Credit Agreement. As</font><font style="display: inline;"> discussed above, as of</font><font style="display: inline;"> September 30, 2015, the Company was </font><font style="display: inline;">not in compliance with </font><font style="display: inline;">the fixed charge coverage </font><font style="display: inline;">ratio and the leverage ratio under the Credit Agreement. On November 3, 2015, t</font><font style="display: inline;">he Company received a waiver from the lenders </font><font style="display: inline;">of the financial covenant violations as of September 30, 2015.</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">The Company anticipates it will be in compliance with its covenants as of December 31, 2015.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, Crocs had </font><font style="display: inline;">$</font><font style="display: inline;">7.7 million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$11.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively, of debt outstanding under </font><font style="display: inline;">five</font><font style="display: inline;"> separate notes payable, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">of which </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">$5.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">4 million and $5.3 million, respectively, </font><font style="display: inline;">represents current installments. As of September 30, 2015, the notes bear interest rates ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.45%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">2.79%</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">and maturities ranging from </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2016</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> to </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">September 2017</font><font style="display: inline;">. As this debt arrangement relates solely to the construction and implementation of an ERP system for use by the entity, interest expense was capitalized to the condensed consolidated balance sheets until the assets were placed into service on January 1, 2015. During the three and nine months ended September 30, 2015, </font><font style="display: inline;">no</font><font style="display: inline;"> interest was capitalized. During the three and nine months ended September 30, 2014, Crocs capitalized </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, in interest expense related to this debt arrangement. Interest rates and payment terms are subject to change as further financing occurs under the Master IPA.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: 2014, the fair value of the Company&#x2019;s debt instruments approximates their reported carrying amounts</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: 2825000 10593000 1857000 2609000 6127000 3439000 1677000 1011000 28019000 5919000 11111000 10989000 5749000 3351000 1889000 8912000 1869000 3765000 3278000 1825000 1010000 443000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Depreciation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">During the three months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$4.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$6.4</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, in depreciation expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.5</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, was recorded in &#x2018;Cost of sales,&#x2019; with the remaining amounts recorded in &#x2018;Selling, general and administrative expenses&#x2019; on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. During the nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;">recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$13.0</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;">$18.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, in depreciation expense of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$1.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;"> for both periods</font><font style="display: inline;"> was recorded in &#x2018;Cost of sales,&#x2019; with the remaining amounts recorded in &#x2018;Selling, general and administrative expenses&#x2019; on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, accumulated depreciation was </font><font style="display: inline;">$106.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$99.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively</font><font style="display: inline;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 319639000 7913000 3005000 5376000 134755000 17230000 814000 3356000 44533000 14590000 13180000 917000 743000 1838000 1918000 61887000 3229000 4355000 245918000 5935000 1910000 1237000 16902000 20372000 676000 5144000 96015000 11795000 9823000 560000 781000 2552000 62325000 3410000 6481000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">8. DERIVATIVE FINANCIAL INSTRUMENTS </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Crocs transacts business in various foreign countries and is therefore exposed to foreign currency exchange rate risk inherent in revenues, costs, and monetary assets and liabilities denominated in non-functional currencies. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In general, </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">enters</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> into foreign currency exchange forward contracts and currency swap derivative instruments to selectively protect against volatility in the value of non-functional currency denominated monetary assets and liabilities, and of future cash flows caused by changes in foreign currency exchange rates. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">As</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> these derivative instruments</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> do not qualify</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> as hedging instruments under the accounting standar</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">ds for derivatives and hedging, they </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">are recorded at fair value as a derivative asset or liability on the balance sheet with their corresponding change in fair value recognized in &#x2018;Foreign currency transaction </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">loss</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, net&#x2019; in the condensed consolidated statements of operations. For purposes of the cash flow statement, Crocs classifies the cash flows </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">from derivative instruments </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">at settlement from undesignated instruments in the same category as the cash flows from the related hedged items, generally within &#x2018;Cash provided by </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">(used in) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">operating activities.&#x2019; </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The following table summarizes the notional amounts of the outstanding foreign currency exchange contracts as of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014. The notional amounts of the derivative financial instruments shown below are denominated in their U.S. Dollar equivalents and represent the amount of all contracts of the foreign currency specified. These notional values do not necessarily represent amounts exchanged by the parties and, therefore, are not a direct measure of the Company&#x2019;s exposure to the foreign currency exchange risks</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <div style="width:100%"><table cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" style="border-collapse:collapse;width: 100.00%;margin-left:0pt;"> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: STOCK</font><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">-BASED COMPENSATION</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Stock-based compensation expense is based on the grant date fair value and is recognized on a straight-line basis over the applicable vesting period. During the three months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.4</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.0</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million, respectively, of pre-tax stock-based compensation expense, of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$2.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">, &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;">and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.1</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$0.2</font><font style="display: inline;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;">, respectively,</font><font style="display: inline;"> is included in cost of sales on the condensed consolidated statements of operations. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font nine months ended </font><font style="display: inline;">September 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded </font><font style="display: inline;">$8.9</font><font As of September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015, Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;">had </font><font style="display: inline;">$17.</font><font style="display: inline;">3</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;million</font><font style="display: inline;"> of total unrecognized </font><font style="display: inline;">stock</font><font style="display: inline;">-based compensation expense related to unvested restricted stock units, net of expected forfeitures, of </font><font style="display: inline;">which </font><font style="display: inline;">$9.7</font><font style="display: inline;"> million is related to time-based awards and </font><font style="display: inline;">$7.6</font><font style="display: inline;"> million is related to performance-based awards. As of September 30, 2015, the unvested RSUs are expected to be amortized over the remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.93</font><font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;years, which consists of a remaining weighted average </font><font style="display: inline;">period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.99</font><font style="display: inline;"> years related to performance-based awards and a remaining weighted average period of </font><font style="display: inline;">1.85</font><font style="display: inline;"> years related to time-based awards.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Appointment of Interim CFO</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">On September&nbsp;7, 2015, Jeffrey J. Lasher resigned as Senior Vice President - Finance and Chief Financial Officer of Crocs. His resignation was effective October&nbsp;1, 2015 and he will remain employed to provide transition services to the Company through November&nbsp;7, 2015. On September&nbsp;7, 2015, the Company appointed Mike Smith as Interim Chief Financial Officer, effective October&nbsp;1, 2015. </font><font style="display: inline;">In connection with his appointment as Interim Chief Financial Officer, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Mr.&nbsp;Smith was granted a </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">RSU</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> award representing the right to receive </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">10,000</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock. The RSUs will vest in </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">three</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> equal annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of the grant date, subject to Mr.&nbsp;Smith&#x2019;s continued employment with the Company through each vesting date</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">. &nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Appointment of CFO</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On November 4, 2015, the board of directors </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">of the Company (the &#x201C;Board&#x201D;) </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">appointed Carrie Teffner as Executive Vice President and Chief Financial Officer, effective December 16, 2015. In connection with her appointment, Ms. Teffner will resign as a member of the Board prior to her start date with the Company. She will serve as the Company&#x2019;s principal financial officer and principal accounting officer. Mike Smith</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> will no longer serve as Interim Chief Financial Officer on her start date.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">Upon the commencement of her employment, Ms. Teffner will be granted a time-vesting RSU award representing the right to receive shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$1,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">-day weighted-average stock price as of the date Ms. Teffner&#x2019;s appointment was publicly announced. The RSUs will vest in </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">three</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> annual installments beginning on the first anniversary of her start date, subject to her continued employment with the Company as of each vesting date.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">In addition, Ms. Teffner will be granted a performance-vesting RSU award, representing the right to receive shares of the Company&#x2019;s common stock equal to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$1,000,000</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">, based on a </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">30</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">-day weighted-average stock price as of the date Ms. Teffner&#x2019;s appointment was publicly announced. The RSU will vest based on the achievement of certain share price levels on or before the fourth anniversary of her start date, subject to continued employment with the Company.&nbsp; </font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 3067000 3067000 3000000 0.38 0.12 -0.32 -0.37 0.37 0.12 -0.32 -0.37 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Earnings per Share</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Basic and diluted earnings per common share (&#x201C;EPS&#x201D;) is presented using the two-class method, which is an earnings allocation formula that determines earnings per share for common stock and any participating securities according to dividend rights and participation rights in undistributed earnings. Under the two-class method, EPS is computed by dividing the sum of distributed and undistributed earnings attributable to common stockholders by the weighted average number of shares of common stock outstanding during the period. A participating security is a security that may participate in undistributed earnings with common stock had those earnings been distributed in any form. The Company&#x2019;s Series A convertible preferred stock (&#x201C;Series A preferred stock&#x201D;) issued in 2014 represents participating securities as holders of the Series A preferred stock are entitled to receive any and all dividends declared or paid on common stock on an as-converted basis. In addition, shares of the Company&#x2019;s non-vested restricted stock and restricted stock unit awards are considered participating securities as they represent unvested share-based payment awards containing non-forfeitable rights to dividends. As such, these participating securities must be included in the computation of EPS pursuant to the two-class method on a pro-rata, as-converted basis. Diluted EPS reflects the potential dilution from securities that could share in the Company&#x2019;s earnings. In addition, the dilutive effect of each participating security</font><font style="display: inline;">, if any,</font><font style="display: inline;"> is calculated using the more dilutive of the two-class method described above. This method assumes that the securities remain in their current form, or the if-converted method, which assumes conversion to common stock as of the beginning of the reporting date. Anti-dilutive securities are excluded from diluted EPS. See </font><font style="display: inline;">Note 12&#x2014;Earnings Per Share</font><font style="display: inline;"> for further discussion.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 12pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-size:12pt;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:12pt 0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">12. EARNINGS PER SHARE</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The following table illustrates the basic and diluted EPS computations for the three and nine months ended September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30</font><font style="display: inline;">, 2015 and 2014:</font> The Series A preferred shares were excluded in the calculation of diluted EPS under the if-converted method because the effect would be anti-dilutive. If converted, Series A preferred stock would represent </font><font style="display: inline;">approximately </font><font style="display: inline;">15.8%</font><font style="display: inline;"> of the Company&#x2019;s common stock outstanding or </font><font style="display: inline;">13.8</font><font style="display: inline;"> million additional common shares, as of </font><font style="display: inline;">September</font><font style="display: inline;"> 30, 2015. The number, price, structure and timing of the repurchases will be at the Company&#x2019;s sole discretion and future repurchases will be evaluated by the Company depending on market conditions, liquidity needs and other factors. Share repurchases may be made in the open market or in privately negotiated transactions. The repurchase authorization does not have an expira</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">tion date and does not obligate</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> Crocs to acquire any particular amount of its common stock. The Board may suspend, modify or terminate the repurchase program at any time without prior notice.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During the three months ended September 30, 2015, Crocs repurchased approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">2.3</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million shares at a weighted average price of </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$14.50</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> per share for an aggregate price of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$33.1</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> excluding related commission charges</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">,</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> under the publicly-announced repurchase plan. style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">7. FAIR VALUE MEASUREMENTS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">GAAP provides for a fair value hierarchy that prioritizes the inputs to the valuation techniques used to measure fair value into three broad levels. Level 1 inputs are quoted market prices in active markets for identical assets or liabilities that the reporting entity has the ability to access at the measurement date. Level 2 inputs are inputs other than quoted market prices included within Level 1 that are observable for the asset or liability, either directly or indirectly. Level 3 inputs are unobservable inputs for the asset or liability.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, our assets subject to fair value measurements consisted solely of cash equivalents of </font><font style="display: inline;">$15.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;">$23.3</font><font style="display: inline;"> million, respectively, which are Level 1 assets.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 1pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Non-Recurring Fair Value Measurements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">The majority of the Company&#x2019;s non-financial instruments, which include inventories, property and equipment and intangible assets, are not required to be carried at fair value on a recurring basis. However, if certain triggering events occur such that a non-financial instrument is required to be evaluated for impairment and the carrying value is not recoverable, the carrying value would be adjusted to the lower of its cost or fair value and an impairment charge would be recorded. During the three months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">5.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and $2.6 million, respectively, in impairment charges associated with the Company&#x2019;s retail locations. During the nine months ended September 30, 2015 and 2014, Crocs recorded $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">7.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million and $5.8 million, respectively, in impairment charges associated with the Company&#x2019;s retail locations</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 78126000 4170000 4931000 62591000 5798000 636000 95587000 4170000 5054000 81406000 4846000 111000 19175000 5451000 12524000 14449000 16901000 18620000 175130000 4170000 6702000 157615000 5945000 698000 182707000 4170000 6674000 166774000 4846000 243000 97004000 1771000 95024000 147000 62000 87120000 1620000 85368000 132000 -4278000 -1290000 -2631000 -2908000 9019000 99000 -2711000 2497000 -6963000 -2620000 2044000 2030000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;"></font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">4. GOODWILL &amp; INTANGIBLE ASSETS</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">The 12009000 -24065000 -27776000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In April 2015, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Standards Update ("ASU") 2015-03: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be </font><font style="display: inline;">presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, </font><font style="display: inline;">consistent with debt discounts. </font><font style="display: inline;">ASU 2015-03 requires retrospective adoption and will be effective for Crocs beginning in the first quarter of 2016. Early adoption is permitted. Crocs does not expect this pronouncement will have a material impact on the condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">I</font><font style="display: inline;">n June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;">ASU 2014-09 </font><font style="display: inline;">becomes effective for</font><font style="display: inline;"> reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2017. Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim</font><font style="display: inline;"> periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. </font><font style="display: inline;">This new standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. </font><font style="display: inline;">Crocs is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on the condensed consolidated financial statements.</font><font style="display: inline;"> Crocs has not yet selected a transition method or determined the effect of the standard on financial reporting once the standard is effective. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. </font><font style="display: inline;">Specifically, t</font><font style="display: inline;">his </font><font style="display: inline;">standard </font><font style="display: inline;">eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or </font><font style="display: inline;">net realizable value</font><font style="display: inline;"> less an approximately normal profit margin when measuring inventory. This standard is effective prospectively beginning January 1, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after September 30, 2015 are not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 4 3 59846000 -13750000 45000 -104537000 178088000 53451000 95383000 29254000 1113000 -5405000 15000 -31755000 38258000 15094000 13475000 9689000 -6743000 -18843000 -113736000 125836000 48884000 58775000 18177000 -20730000 -6549000 -29927000 15746000 11734000 178000 3834000 14635000 4952000 12171000 4166000 82307000 26629000 73181000 23323000 96206000 31320000 85176000 27431000 736000 261000 176000 58000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <div style="width:100%"><table style="width:100%;" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td style="width:0pt;"><p style="width:0pt;font-size:0pt;"></p></td><td valign="top" align="left" style="width: 18.00pt; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#x201C;Crocs,&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">&#x201C;we,&#x201D; &#x201C;our&#x201D; or &#x201C;us&#x201D;) are engaged in the design, development, manufacturing, marketing and distribution of footwear, apparel and accessories for men, women and children.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Basis of Presentation</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements have been prepared in accordance with accounting principles generally accepted in the United States (&#x201C;GAAP&#x201D;) for interim financial information and with the rules&nbsp;and regulations of the Securities and Exchange Commission (&#x201C;SEC&#x201D;) for reporting on Form&nbsp;10-Q. Accordingly, these financial statements do not include all information required for complete financial statements. In the opinion of management, these condensed consolidated financial statements reflect all adjustments (consisting solely of normal recurring matters) considered necessary for a fair statement of the results for the interim periods presented. The accompanying unaudited condensed consolidated financial statements and these notes thereto should be read in conjunction with </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">our Annual Report on Form 10-K for the year ended December 31, 2014</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">. The results of operations for any interim period are not necessarily indicative of results for the full year.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">The preparation of financial statements in conformity with GAAP requires management to make estimates and assumptions that affect the reporting amounts of assets and liabilities at the date of the financial statements and the reported amounts of revenue and expense during the reporting period. Estimates and assumptions are used in accounting for, among other things, the valuation of acquisition-related assets and liabilities, allowances for uncollectable accounts, taxes and related valuation allowances, loss contingencies, fair value measurements, impairment assessments, useful lives of long-lived assets and share-based compensation. Actual results could differ from those estimates.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Recently Issued Accounting Pronouncements</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Debt Issuance Costs</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-indent:18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In April 2015, the Financial Accounting Standards Board ("FASB") issued Accounting Standards Update ("ASU") 2015-03: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Presentation of Debt Issuance Costs,</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> which requires that debt issuance costs related to a recognized debt liability be </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">presented in the balance sheet as a direct deduction from the carrying amount of that debt liability, </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">consistent with debt discounts. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ASU 2015-03 requires retrospective adoption and will be effective for Crocs beginning in the first quarter of 2016. Early adoption is permitted. Crocs does not expect this pronouncement will have a material impact on the condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Share-Based Payments</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">I</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">n June 2014, the FASB issued ASU 2014-12 in response to the EITF consensus on Issue 13-D. The ASU clarifies that entities should treat performance targets that can be met after the requisite service period of a share-based payment award as performance conditions that affect vesting. Therefore, an entity would not record compensation expense related to an award for which transfer to the employee is contingent on the entity&#x2019;s satisfaction of a performance target until it becomes probable that the performance target will be met. The ASU does not contain any new disclosure requirements. This ASU is effective for all entities for reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2015. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Revenue Recognition</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 12pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In May 2014, the FASB issued their final standard on revenue from contracts with customers. The standard, issued as ASU No. 2014-09: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Revenue from Contracts with Customers (Topic 606)</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> by the FASB, outlines a single comprehensive model for entities to use in accounting for revenue arising from contracts with customers and supersedes most current revenue recognition guidance, including industry-specific guidance. The core principle of the revenue model is that &#x201C;an entity recognizes revenue to depict the transfer of promised goods or services to customers in an amount that reflects the consideration to which the entity expects to be entitled in exchange for those goods or services.&#x201D; </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">ASU 2014-09 </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">becomes effective for</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> reporting periods (including interim periods) beginning after December 15, 2017. Early application is permitted for reporting periods (including interim</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> periods) beginning after December 15, 2016. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">This new standard permits the use of either the retrospective or cumulative effect transition method. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Crocs is currently evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on the condensed consolidated financial statements.</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> Crocs has not yet selected a transition method or determined the effect of the standard on financial reporting once the standard is effective. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Inventory</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">In July 2015, the FASB issued ASU No. 2015-11: </font><font style="display: inline;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Simplifying the Measurement of Inventory</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">, which modifies existing requirements regarding measuring inventory at the lower of cost or market. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Specifically, t</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">his </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">standard </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">eliminates the need to determine and consider replacement cost or </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">net realizable value</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;"> less an approximately normal profit margin when measuring inventory. This standard is effective prospectively beginning January 1, 2017, with early adoption permitted. The Company is currently </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">evaluating the impact that this pronouncement will have on its condensed consolidated financial statements. </font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;color:#000000;">Other new pronouncements issued but not effective until after September 30, 2015 are not expected to have a material impact on the Company&#x2019;s financial position, results of operations or cash flows.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> <p style="margin:0pt;font-family:Times New Roman;;font-size: 10pt"><font style="display: inline;"></font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div> 2201000 3878000 25968000 23587000 19650000 18891000 29306000 11739000 97337000 87420000 12277000 12430000 170000 -416000 388000 217000 -6000 405000 4484000 1776000 588000 5000 5229000 1684000 90093000 75928000 9656000 3088000 338000 6230000 75000 94000 5166000 8900000 787000 261000 29457000 7572000 13891000 4235000 8233000 3067000 8833000 3000000 0.001 0.001 4000000 4000000 0 0 30156000 29782000 1300000 1255000 182220000 174000 68288000 50188000 9129000 25258000 202300000 147200000 <div> <div style="margin-left:0pt;margin-right:0pt;"> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;">6. RESTRUCTURING ACTIVITIES</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;font-size:10pt;">Restructuring</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">On July 21, 2014, Crocs announced strategic plans for long-term improvement and growth of the business. </font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">These plans comprise four key initiatives including (1) streamlining the global product and marketing portfolio, (2) reducing direct investment in smaller geographic markets, (3) creating a more efficient organizational structure by reducing excess overhead and enhancing the decision making process, and (4) closing or converting retail locations around the world. The initial effects of these plans were incurred in 2014 and are continuing throughout 2015. Crocs</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> recorded restructuring charges of $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">1.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">&nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">million and $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">7.5</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million during the three and nine month periods ended September 30, 2015, respectively</font><font style="display: inline;color:#000000;font-size:10pt;">. &nbsp;</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">During 2015, Crocs currently estimates restructuring costs related to store closures and changes in organizational structure of approximately </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$8.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million to </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">$12.0</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;"> million, but the Company can make no assurance that actu</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;">al costs will not differ.</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;border-bottom:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;border-top:1pt none #D9D9D9 ;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-weight:bold;font-style:italic;color:#000000;">Retail Store Closings</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;line-height:normal;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;">&nbsp;</font> </p> <p style="margin:0pt;text-align:justify;text-justify:inter-ideograph;font-family:Times New Roman;font-size: 10pt"> <font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">As mentioned above, the Company plans to close additional retail locations around the globe. As such, Crocs expects to incur certain exit costs specific to store closures including operating lease termination costs, rent obligations for leased facilities, net of expected sublease income, and other expenses in association with this plan. During the three and nine month periods ended September 30, 2015, Crocs </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">closed </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">2</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">18</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> company</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">-operated retail locations that</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> were identified in the initial </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">restructuring plan</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">, respectively. </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">These locations were selected for closure by management based on historical and projected profitability levels, relocation plans, and other factors. As of September 30, 2015 and December 31, 2014, Crocs had a liability of approximately $</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">2.7</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> million and </font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">$4.9</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;"> million, respectively, related to locations to be closed and other reductions in workforce in accrued restructuring on the condensed consolidated balance sheets. The calculation of accrued store closing reserves primarily includes future minimum lease payments from the date of closure to the end of the remaining lease term, net of contractual or estimated sublease income. Crocs records the liability at fair value in the period the store is closed</font><font style="display: inline;font-size:10pt;color:#000000;">.</font> </p> <p><font size="1"> </font></p> </div> </div>
